segments.text: It was Ned, this is a date for you tonight at the party over at the judge's house.
And so that was a very memorable singing cadet trip.
I believe that was the sophomore spring semester that that happened.
This is a note to the typist, an editorial note.
If I'm not mistaken,

this Mr. Smith or his brother came to the campus to try to lobby the board then called the board of directors to vote against coeducation and I with another young faculty member in history we took off our coats and ties so we might not be recognized very much and stood in the background as he met with what he

called the leaders of the senior class in the hallway of the MSC on second floor straight above the check-in desk and as I recall he told them that he urged them to go and argue against co-education non-compulsory core higher admission requirements and so forth and he lost his audience though when he told the group
that A&M was not teaching the practical things now.
They weren't giving enough attention to the slide rule, to their verbs and their pronouns and their diagramming of sentences, and that you really didn't need any math beyond trigonometry.
And as he was saying those things, we could see the look on the senior class members' faces like this old man has lost it.
He's out of touch.

and he asked the senior class president to go with him to join him in speaking against the changes, and the senior class president, whomever it was that year, stood up and identified himself and said, the senior class has not yet discussed these topics.
No one, neither I nor anyone else, can speak for the senior class on these topics.
They can speak as individuals.
but you cannot argue that the senior class is for or against any of this.
Well, as a result, there were almost no students that went with it.
Back to singing cadets.
Do you remember any... His grandson, T.M.
Smith's grandson, was T.M.
Smith III.
He was a classmate of mine in Class 63.
During your singing cadet experience, do you remember any particularly proud moments?

Oh, yes, yes, getting Mickey Mantle's signature and helping him walk downstairs as, you call it a prank if you want to, but as you know, the singing cadets were escorts to the Miss Teenage American pageant for a good number of years, and I made, I think, three of those pageants, and one of those pageants...
The judges for the pageant, Mickey Mantle was a judge.
This actress by the name of White, Betty White, Betty White was a judge.
A guy named Al Ludden or something, Al Ludden maybe was a judge.

I got all their signatures, and from the stage, the girls would come down these stairs, and the judges were up there, and during one of the rehearsals, Mickey Mantle was going to walk down these stairs, and I grabbed his arm and helped him down the stairs like I would one of the girls.
Yeah, that was very memorable.
And my last year in the cadets...
I had laid out the one semester, so I actually graduated in January of 64 instead of May or June of 63 because of laying out that semester.
And I guess it was that last semester in October of 63,

I was married and my wife got pregnant and we went to the Miss Teenage America pageant and the guy that was really producing the Miss Teenage America pageant was one of the big owners of Six Flags and a bunch of us went to Six Flags and my wife and I and with her pregnant we rode everything at Six Flags.
I remember that very well.
What moments of singing
a special A&M song did you feel most proud?
Where, when, or how?
Well, you have to advance my career a long way.
I was a dean of undergraduate affairs in the College of Engineering.
Bob Boone could not make a commencement exercise.
And Bob Boone called me and he said, you're leading commencement spirit of Aggieland.
Can you do it?
And I said, what a pleasure.
Yes, I guess as far as a proud moment to be at commencement and do that for Bob Boone, who no one replaced Bob Boone, number one.
But to do that was just most memorable.
And, of course, you know, we always performed very, very strong patriotic and solid religious programs when I was in the cadets.
And even after that, and I have made many of the spring concerts and gone to the stage when Boone would ask former cadets to come to the stage.
So all of those were very, very...
very, very special to me.
But I think leading the crowd in the spirit of a commencement had to be very, very special.
Did you get involved in any MSC activities?
Yes, I participated again in the Ham Radio Club and three or four other committees within the MSC.
I don't know that I can even tell you what all those committees were now.
How many were in the Ham Radio Club in your years?
Oh, goodness, maybe 20, 25 maybe.
And I kept up with some of those guys.
And where was your radio room?
It was on the second floor of the MSC.

little small small room that looked out on the front side of the student center had one little window that you could see out the front side and antenna was mounted up on the on the top of the building and we spent a lot of our time trying to get money to upgrade equipment
But it was on the second floor.
Have any idea how long that lasted?
How many years?
The radio club?
It was in existence when I got there, and it was there when I left, and I don't... W5AC may still exist.
I don't know.
And you don't know whether it goes back to the 20s or not?
I want to say that it goes way, way back, even to maybe the time when the first game was broadcast.
I don't know whether there was an association or relationship between those two or not, but just the fact that it's W5AC tells you it's an old, old, old station because of the call letters.
Number one, because it's just a two-call.
And it's very early in the alphabet, AC.
So W5AC was very, very early in the alphabet.
owned in the Hound Radio community.
Did you get involved in any local religious, did you attend?
Yes, I attended church very religiously, Haskell.
At Northgate?
No, at Little Church of Christ over in Bryan.
That's where I met my wife.
And my wife was...
working at what was then called the Texas A&M Press and it's what is called today the Printing Center.

But they did everything, anything that was printed or published on the campus of A&M was done at the A&M Press and my wife is on the front page of the battalion fall of 1963 holding up Texas A&M University.
That was when the name changed.
In fact, my Aggie ring, Class of 63, reads A&M College of Texas.
And you'll notice my Bachelor of Science diploma says Texas A&M University.
So that's when it happened.
I got caught by laying out that semester.
I'm not an A&M College of Texas graduate.
I'm a Texas A&M University graduate.
All right.
So you're in the Corps when you meet her.
When y'all were courting, where would y'all go?
Oh, gosh.
Where would you go to eat?
We would go to a place where First Federal Savings and Loans, First Federal Bank is now.
That was the best place, I mean the highestfalutin place in town, if you will, and that was called, oh, goodness, Haskell.
I'll think of it before the day is over.
On down the road past there was, over on South College, was the Triangle and the Texan.
And we could also go there at the Circle, which was at Northgate.
There was a hamburger joint there on the circle.
You could go there.
There were two or three greasy spoons at Northgate.
Nothing like what's there now, but two or three little old cafes there.
You could go there, but I didn't take Miss Walton there very often when we were recording.
If we went to a movie, we went to...
a Bryan movie.
The campus was a little bit more rowdy, so I wouldn't take it.
I said I wouldn't take it.
We typically did not go there.
And so that was pretty much it.
Being church crash members, you all didn't go out and do wild drinking.
No, no drinking and no dancing.
Not that we had anything against dancing, either one.
I was just never were much dancers.
It was fairly laid back.
I remember before we married in December of what would, when I was in the core of December of my senior years when we married.
And then I graduated in, that would be December of 62.
I graduated in January of 64, which is just a little over a year after that.
And where did y'all live then?
Well, now, just before, I was in dorm two when we got married, and she lived over on Ash Street in College Station, just over at what we call the Eastgate area.
And she and her mother would make cakes and pies and coffee and what have you.
And Miss Walton would, she was a Douglas, Etta Douglas, Etta would call the guard room and one of the fish would come up to my room and say, Mr. Walton, sir, the lady is on the phone.
We didn't have phones in the rooms those days.
I'd go down to the dorm room, and I'd call her, and she'd say, hey, I got a pie made, or I got some coffee made.
Would you like to come over?
And I would.
We would go over and visit with her.
And when we married, this is a long story, and I guess maybe I can tell you the shortened version and see what you think about it as far as the appropriateness is concerned.
When I took my physical exam...
for advanced contract, to get a military advanced contract.
I failed the physical.
And it was, I thought they were picking on me because I failed it.
And the reason I failed it is because of the little accident that I'd had as a freshman.
And I had a minor back injury.
I mean, it wasn't bad, but minor back injury.
I just literally begged them to let me be examined again, that I really wanted the advance contract.
But in an interim period of time, there was a professor of civil engineering named Jim Bob Beatty.
And Jim Bob Beatty taught water, sewer, and sanitation.
And the Medical Service Corps was looking for civil engineering graduates to go into the Medical Service Corps to run water systems, sanitation systems, sewer systems, and what have you.
And those were what were called direct commissions.
And they would just take you right straight as a BS graduate.
And what was not only so great about it, if you really qualified what they were looking for, you got to go in as a first lieutenant rather than a second lieutenant, just like the vets did.
So Jim Bob Beatty was a very, he was a special prof. Jim Beatty and I communicated very well.
I had told him about not passing my physical and didn't know what I was going to do, and he said, well, I'll tell you what you do.
You just take some specialization in sanitation above and beyond the basic water and sewer, and I know how to help you.
And sure enough, he did.
He got me in communication with the Medical Service Corps, and it was kind of left at, yeah, you get your BS degree and you have these courses.
We'll take you.
We need you.
And so I was preparing to do that, as a matter of fact, and...
Then I got married, and when I got married, Colonel Joe Davis was a commandant, and I went over and I talked to him.

I said, you know, I really don't know how to say this, don't know what to say, but you know the problem that I've had on getting my reexamination and what have you, and I said, I have maybe an opportunity to go into the medical service corps when I graduate.
What should I do?
They said, well, what are your other plans?
Well, I'm going to get married, you know, in December.
And he said, well, he said, the only smart thing for you to do is stay drilling ceremonies in the Corps and forget about advanced contract.
I mean, you already got it.
I mean, you know, goodness, go for it.
So I got married, and I stayed through that semester in the Corps, and I became a civilian student the last part of my senior year.
So I was in the Corps, out of the Corps, in the Corps, and out of the Corps again.
And to make a long story short, my wife and I were married seven months when she got pregnant.
Okay?
Now, this brings up another little problem of now what do you do?
And by the way, you asked me what started it.
Where did you live?
We lived over on Eccles Street in a garage apartment and moved from Eccles Street into Hensel Apartments, Married Student Housing.
Do you remember what did Hensel cost then?
And that included all utilities and everything, $60.
And where did you all acquire the vast amount of furniture that it must have been?
Oh, we got it from my mother, her mother and dad, my brother, my sister, wherever we could find something.
That's the only thing.
Castoffs.
Castoffs.
Anyway, I ended up dropping out as a core student there.
And we lived there.
And like I say, we were married seven months.
She got pregnant.
When I graduated medical service corps, do you want me?
We don't want married men.
And we certainly don't want a married man that's got a pregnant wife.
So I set it out, Haskell.
And you were anxious to...
Yes, what I really thought I was going towards, so I set it out.
No draft, no nothing.
I mean, I was just sitting there, and the only official record that was on file anywhere is that I had not passed the physical for my advance contracts, and they left me alone.
Meanwhile, your grades are getting better.
Oh, absolutely.
I'm studying with these Army and Air Force officers, Captain Eads and Major Davis and Captain Custer, and all my grades are getting better and better.
I'm making better and better impressions on my profs.
You know, Walton may amount to something someday.
If you were summarizing that for a student today, what were the secrets of the improvement of your work?
Haskell, I think, you know, we can make excuses, you know, and I've always had a, you know, propensity to make an excuse when I really needed to.
I could say very poor preparation to begin with.
I had no study skills.
I was the auditorium of a class of 20 kids, like, big deal.
You know, that was because the other 19, well, you know how that goes.
I was not prepared at all for those first couple of years.
And it was a real, I mean, it was just really tough to hang in.
And Haskell, they weeded us, they weeded students out in those days.
I'm sorry, you know, my core outfit probably started out with 40 freshmen.
It was probably 10 or 12 of those kids that graduated, period.
And only two or three of those in engineering.
So it was a terrible thing to get through it to begin with.
So there was a poor preparation, but I had no study skills, absolutely none whatsoever.
Did anybody tell you?
to improve your study skills, or did you just graduate?
No, I don't think so.
I think that was something that you just, after a while, you assimilated and through a process of osmosis, maybe you just got better.
And I'm going to say, in all seriousness, those three officers that I've called by name helped me develop a discipline
I mean, they would say, at this time every day, this is what we're going to do.
And I had one of those guys typically as a lab partner in almost all of my later junior and all of my senior classes.
And, yeah, things just improved drastically.
And even when we went to Junction for summer surveying camp, those three guys and I were on a four-man team at Junction.
Describe Junction.
junction server.
Brutal.
You're talking about Bear Bryant and his football players out there.
Listen, we didn't have any better.
It was brutal.
We got up at daylight.
Y'all were out there after
Yeah, we were out there after the Bryant Saga, but there were two groups that went to Junction every summer.

One group, the geology students, they went out there for looking at formations and cracked rocks and all that sort of thing that they do, and we went out to do surveying and stream gauging and to run road routes up the side of those little hills out there around Junction.
About how many were in your group?
Oh, goodness, we probably had 40 or 50, maybe, at Junction in civil engineering.
And these are primarily sophomores to be?
No, no, these are seniors to be, are already deep into their senior year.
I postponed mine to that summer after my, quote, senior year.
I went in the summer of 63, I believe it was.
Well, no, it wasn't because I was married.
Who was in charge?
Uncle Ed Harrington.
I don't know if you remember Ed Harrington or not, and Joe Orr, and Bob Olson.
What was the described typical routine?
Oh, and the guy that ran Junction for the freshmen out there.
Well, see, there were those two groups, but they had a freshman program at Junction where

I don't know if that was a beginning of fish camp or what, but the kids would go out there and they'd take freshman English, freshman history maybe, and Kutash, D. Kutash was kind of running the operations of the university at that time.
That's K-U-T-A-S-H. That sounds close, yes.
I think that's right.
Yeah, Kutash, D. Kutash's.
It went like this.
The civil engineering students were dorm tent advisors.
The buildings out there were half walls and roll-up tents on the outside, and they would have 15 or 20, 24 freshmen or something, and one civil engineering student was the...
was the dorm master, if you would, for all those students.
And we didn't interact with them educationally or anything.
We just made sure that they went to bed at night and got up the next morning.
Well, we got up at daylight every morning, went to chow,
and hit the classroom for a brief introduction of what we were going to do that day.
And we surveyed or streamgaged all day until 5 o'clock.
And we'd come in high o'clock, blistered, hot, sweaty, chased a few jackrabbits probably in the process.
We'd come back in, go through a debriefing, and we would draw up our surveys and what have you.
It was a tremendous experience, really hands-on experience of what a
In effect, civil engineers became surveyors in those days.
You could register as a surveyor by having a civil engineering degree.
As you look back on it now,
Was it a good sound?
Absolutely.
I wish that they still did something similar to that.
If it's not a surveying camp, some type of a summer practicum where you get out and get your feet hot and sweaty and dirty and you learn some real practical things.
And we used calculators back in those days.
You remember the old Monroe?
You remember the name Monroe?
And what was the other name of those calculators?
But you would input and you'd have to crank it, you know?
to get the decimal and the carrying your tens forward.
Those were the calculators that we had in those days.
The University of Missouri has operated something like that, particularly for geology and the engineers.
They own about 5,000 acres about five miles outside Lander, Wyoming.
And can you imagine how much fun it is to spend six weeks in Wyoming?
Yes.
I was really just going to see A&M give up Junction and let it go to Tech.
I really was.
I was just heartbroken when that happened.
awful blunder.
That Llano River and the pecan trees down there in those bottoms there at Junction where we had that camp was just magnificent.
I still have very vivid memories.
And swimming in those holes in the Llano.
Oh, I can remember that.
What I've learned so far, correct me if I'm wrong, all the students pretty well behaved themselves.
Didn't go into town and cause any trouble.
No, that's not true.
It's not true?
That's not true.
Yeah, there was...
Yeah, there was always the troublemakers that went into town.
Went up on the hill, they called it, up on the hill.
Oh, that's right.
And went up on the hill and drank beer and would come back in and Kutash or Harrington or somebody would catch them and it would be trouble.

i i will i will tell this story it's not one that i'm particularly proud of but it's a part of history haskell and i think most of us confess as we get older the things that we did in our younger days of indiscretion but uh these three uh maybe i
There were three officers, I won't call names, that were older men and myself and a boy from Columbus, Texas.
He was also married.
We'd travel back and forth from Junction to Bryan College Station on weekends to see our wives.
And we were going back out to Junction the 4th of July weekend.
And we stopped at Milano, Texas.
Now, let's get our words right.
Milano, Texas, which is just up the road here outside of Caldwell.
I'm sorry, Hearn, between Hearn and Cut-Off up through Cameron.
We stopped at Milano and got a barbecued goat.
There was a barbecue going on, and we stopped to get some barbecued goat.
And the three older guys had iced down some refreshments.
It was hot, no air conditioning in the vehicles.
It was hot, unbelievably hot.
And we were driving back, stopped at Milano.
They had some ice-down refreshments, and we all ate some barbecued, some cabrita, and they were drinking a little bit of refreshment.
I was driving, was not.
And as a matter of fact, I won't say that I never did.
I sampled and tried to find out what that was like in my early years at A&M.
But I was not drinking.
And we got from Milano to Llano, Texas, just outside Junction.
And then the 4th of July weekend, these three officers had some fireworks with them.
And they threw those fireworks on the courthouse lawn in Atlanta, Texas, and we got stopped by the city marshal or whatever he was.
And the report was forwarded over to Junction.
Ed Harrington, Dr. Harrington, got the report that there were some Aggie civil engineering students trying to blow up the courthouse over Atlanta.
And that was kind of in jest, too, you know, that they'd been in some meanness.
When they stopped us, they just said,
If you have another weekend or two that you're going from Junction to Bryan College Station, drive around Llano, okay?
Don't come through Llano again.
And even that, I think, probably was in jest.
But when we got to Junction, Bob Olson met us.
before we ever got to the adjunct, to the campus there, and said, Dr. Harrington is terribly upset.
He has heard that you guys were trying to blow up the courthouse over at Llano, and I'm just telling you that for your own good.
And when we got there, we got a real lecture from Ed Harrington, and
And no one was really intoxicated, although those three guys had been drinking.

The next morning in class at 6.45 or 7 o'clock, whatever time we went to the classroom every morning, he just announced that, I just want you to know there was some hell raising over in Leno yesterday, and we don't tolerate that.
Didn't call any names, and it was over with.
In summary, did he handle it the way you think he should have?
Yes, he was very professional in handling it, but cut all four of us a letter grade.
The four of us got D's in that summer class, and we were the top four students in the class.
We had the best product, did the best work, but he cut us a letter grade.
And I look back on that and say, well, I don't blame him.
Sure, why not?
I probably have made that kind of a harsh decision as a prof myself.
Let's see, other activity, special things.
Mentioned Gyne Hall, MSC.
Did you ever have any experience with the Quack Shack, the hospital?
Oh, yes, I did, Haskell, and a couple of times when I really didn't, I went to the Quack Shack to avoid harassment.
You could always go to the Quack Shack and get a, what did they call those?
You got some little, it was a little form that said that you, you didn't have to drill for 24 hours, whatever it was, and you could get rid of the nonsense for sure.
I went over to Quack Shack and did that a couple times.
I admit that, yes, I did.
I also went over when I had a blister on my bottom from brooms.
I got whacked a few times with a broom, an upperclassman, and it made a blister and kind of got infected, and I went over and...
They wouldn't know where it came from, and I told them it had fallen down, and, you know, and they went, oh, that's a blister, blister.
It's a blood-type blister.
You don't get that from falling.
And I never told them where it came from, but they treated it and gave me a shot, probably a penicillin or something.
It went about my merry way, but that probably was the extent of my association with the quack shack.
But, you know, it was right there at the end of dorm 14.
You walked out of dorm 14, and the quack shack was right there in front of you.
Describe the student body in general when you were here.
Where were they from, family, attitude, philosophy, etc.
The student body was very, as far as geographic distribution, I thought it was very diverse.
We had the Houston kids and Dallas-Fort Worth kids.
We had a lot of kids from Atlanta and Jefferson and Marshall and Queen City and Shreveport and Wascom and, you know, and McAllen.
And we had folks from all around.
I thought it was rather diverse geographically.
We obviously were essentially all white, all male.
But were there some Hispanics?
Oh, yes, there were, I won't say a large number, but a very significant number of Hispanics.
German, Czech?
Oh, yeah, Bobby Zawczyk and these guys, yeah, there were all sorts of, yeah, from ethnic background, yeah, German, Czech.
Did it matter?
No, no.
I mean, we were all there together.
I have very fond memories of Ramundo Riojas, one of my classmates from Mexico, George Gutierrez, a lot of Hispanic civil engineering students that I went to school with.
No, it didn't matter.
I mean, we were just a group.
And Catholics and Protestants?
